<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-641-862  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 641 862.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  August 1990 v8 n8 p195(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Data basics. (methods of data validation) (includes relatedarticles on Pinnacle Publishing's dGE 3.0 and on Paradox software)(tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Mistakes in data entry can spoil or limit the usefulness of a database, but computer users can use data validation procedures tocatch such errors soon after they are entered.andP;  For date andnumeric fields, the data base designer can identify implicitlimits and put them into a list for the application to checkagainst user input.andP;  Field-by-field validation is superior toscreen-by-screen validation because it is faster.andP;  When entriesviolate the designated limits, error messages should come up andusers must be able to type new answers right away.andP;  Error messageswork best if they are informative and friendly, but also short.andO;In dBASE III Plus validation is possible with rule-checkingroutines, while in dBASE IV it is handled more easily with a'VALID' clause.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   dBASE III Plus (Data base management system) (user education)dBASE IV (Data base management system) (user education).andO;Topic:     Data ManagementData Base Management SystemsTutorialError CheckingValidation.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Validating a field entry. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>